This paper evaluates a land reform program in Brazil that includes both asset transfers (land) and infrastructure improvement grants. The program provides land transfers to landless farmers along with additional grants for infrastructure improvements. While it's not a traditional graduation program, it does include both productive asset transfers (Component B) and cash support in the form of infrastructure grants (Component A). The study uses quasi-experimental methods with propensity score matching to evaluate impacts on investments, assets, and income over a 2006-2010 period.
